{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}
{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}
[[File:1897 Sam Woods.jpg|thumb|Sam Woods]]
'''Sam Woods''' (10 May 1846 – 23 November 1915) was a British trade unionist and politician who served as a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) in the 1890s.

Born at [[Peasley Cross]] in [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], Woods began working in [[coal mining]] at the age of seven.  He was elected as a pit [[checkweighman]] in 1875 and became strongly involved in trade unionism, joining the [[Lancashire and Cheshire Miners' Federation]] in 1881.  When this merged into the [[Miners' Federation of Great Britain]] (MFGB) in 1889, Woods became the organisation's first vice president.

In the [[United Kingdom general election, 1892|1892 general election]], Woods was elected as a [[Liberal-Labour (UK)|Lib–Lab]] MP for [[Ince (UK Parliament constituency)|Ince]].  In Parliament, he agitated for the [[Coal Mines Regulation Act 1908|Eight Hours Bill]], and in 1894 he was elected as the [[General Secretary of the TUC|Secretary of the Parliamentary Committee]] of the [[Trades Union Congress]] (TUC).  He lost his seat at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1895|1895 general election]], but was re-elected for [[Walthamstow (UK Parliament constituency)|Walthamstow]] at a [[Walthamstow by-election, 1897|by-election in 1897]].  However, he lost the seat in [[United Kingdom general election, 1900|1900]] following confusion over his stance on the [[Second Boer War]].

While broadly supportive of the [[British Labour Party#Labour Representation Committee|Labour Representation Committee]], Woods remained a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] and joined the [[National Democratic League]].  His health failing, he resigned his TUC post in 1904, but retained his vice presidency of the MFGB to prevent [[Robert Smillie]] gaining election.

An elderly persons home is named after him in [[Ashton in Makerfield]].

